00:00:55.100 --> 00:01:01.719
Intro
So in the colonial era, most American women

00:01:01.719 --> 00:01:05.680
of European descent lived lives much like
those of their European counterparts: They

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:10.610
were legally and socially subservient to men
and trapped within a patriarchal structure.

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:14.890
Lower and working class women were actually
more equal to men of their own classes, but

00:01:14.890 --> 00:01:19.080
only because they were, like, equally poor.
As usual, it all comes back to economics.

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:23.900
In general, throughout world history, the
higher the social class, the greater the restrictions

00:01:23.900 --> 00:01:28.619
on women—although high class women have
traditionally had the lowest mortality rates,

00:01:28.619 --> 00:01:32.840
which is one of the benefits of you know doors
and extra lifeboats and whatnot. So at least

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:35.350
you get to enjoy that oppression for many
years.

00:01:35.350 --> 00:01:39.270
As previously noted, American women did participate
in the American Revolution, but they were

00:01:39.270 --> 00:01:44.080
still expected to marry and have kids rather
than, like, pursue a career. Under the legal

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:49.450
principle of “coverture” actually husbands
held authority over the person, property and

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:52.590
choices of their wives.
Also since women weren’t permitted to own

00:01:52.590 --> 00:01:57.119
property and property ownership was a precondition
for voting, they were totally shut out of

00:01:57.119 --> 00:02:00.150
the political process.
Citizens of the new Republic were therefore

00:02:00.150 --> 00:02:06.049
definitionally male, but women did still improve
their status via the ideology of “Republican

00:02:06.049 --> 00:02:08.280
Motherhood.”
Women were important to the new Republic because

00:02:08.280 --> 00:02:13.590
they were raising children—ESPECIALLY MALE
CHILDREN—who would become the future voters,

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:18.180
legislators, and honorary doctors of America.
So women couldn’t themselves participate

00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:22.030
in the political process, but they needed
to be educated some because they were going

00:02:22.030 --> 00:02:26.290
to potty train those who would later participate
in the political process. What’s that? There

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:30.040
were no potties? Really?
Apparently instead of potties they had typhoid.

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:33.900
Actually it was a result of not having potties.
So even living without rights in a pottyless

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:38.090
nation, the Republican Mother idea allowed
women access to education, so that they could

00:02:38.090 --> 00:02:42.450
teach their children. Also women—provided
they weren’t slaves--were counted in determining

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:46.940
the population of a state for representation
purposes, so that was at least an acknowledgement

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:50.550
that they were at, like, five fifths human.
And then the market revolution had profound

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:54.849
effects on American women, too, because as
production shifted from homes to factories,

00:02:54.849 --> 00:02:59.910
it shifted away from women doing the producing.
This led to the so-called “cult of domesticity,”

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:03.540
which like most cults, I am opposed to.
That’s right, Stan, I’m opposed to the

00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:08.940
Blue Oyster Cult, The Cult, The Cult of Personality
by In Living Color, and the three remaining

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:11.769
Shakers.
Sorry, Shakers. But who are we kidding? You’re

00:03:11.769 --> 00:03:16.280
not watching. You’re too busy dancing.
The cult of domesticity decreed that a woman’s

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:21.340
place was in the home, so rather than making
stuff, the job of women was to enable their

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:26.340
husbands to make stuff, by providing food
and a clean living space, but also by providing

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:32.099
what our favorite historian Eric Foner called
“non-market values like love, friendship,

00:03:32.099 --> 00:03:36.599
and mutual obligation,” which is the way
we talk about puppies these days.

00:03:36.599 --> 00:03:41.019
And indeed that’s in line with actual story
titles from early 19th century American women’s

00:03:41.019 --> 00:03:46.250
magazines, like “Woman, a Being to Come
Home To” and “Woman: Man’s Best Friend.”

