The truth is, most American women had no chance

00:05:32.499 --> 00:05:37.409
to work for profit outside their houses, so
many women found work outside traditional

00:05:37.409 --> 00:05:41.080
spheres in reform movements.
Okay, let’s go to the Thought Bubble.

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:44.499
Reform movements were open to women partly
because if women were supposed to be the moral

00:05:44.499 --> 00:05:48.649
center of the home, they could also claim
to be the moral conscience of the nation.

00:05:48.649 --> 00:05:52.889
Thus it didn’t seem out of the ordinary
for women to become active in the movement

00:05:52.889 --> 00:05:56.999
to build asylums for the mentally ill, for
instance, as Dorothea Dix was, or to take

00:05:56.999 --> 00:06:01.800
the lead in sobering the men of America. Many
of the most famous advocates for legally prohibiting

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:06.689
the sale of alcohol in the US were women,
like Carry Nation attacked bars with a hatchet

00:06:06.689 --> 00:06:10.509
and not because she’d had a few too many.
The somewhat less radical Frances Willard

00:06:10.509 --> 00:06:14.879
founded the Women’s Christian Temperance
Union in 1874, which would be one of the most

00:06:14.879 --> 00:06:18.669
powerful lobbying groups in the United States
by the end of the 19th century. And women

00:06:18.669 --> 00:06:23.369
gave many temperance lectures featuring horror
stories of men who, rather than seeking refuge

00:06:23.369 --> 00:06:27.749
from the harsh competition of the market economy
and the loving embrace of their homes, found

00:06:27.749 --> 00:06:33.159
solace at the bottom of a glass or at the
end of a beer hose. And by the way, yes, there

00:06:33.159 --> 00:06:38.080
were bars that allowed you to drink as much
beer as you could, from a hose, for a nickel.

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:41.770
Today, these establishments are known as frat
houses. These temperance lectures would tell

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:46.080
of men spending all their hard earned money
on drink, leaving wives and children—there

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:50.589
were always children—starving and freezing,
because in the world of the temperance lecture,

00:06:50.589 --> 00:06:55.789
it was always winter. Now don’t get me wrong:
Prohibition was a disaster, because 1. Freedom,

00:06:55.789 --> 00:06:59.889
and 2. It’s the only time we had to amend
the constitution to be like, “Just kidding

00:06:59.889 --> 00:07:03.839
about that other amendment,” but it’s
worth remembering that back then people drank

00:07:03.839 --> 00:07:08.719
WAY more than we do now, and also that alcohol
is probably a greater public health issue

00:07:08.719 --> 00:07:13.189
than some recreational drugs that remain illegal.
But regardless, the temperance movement made

00:07:13.189 --> 00:07:18.449
a huge difference in American life because
eventually, male and female supporters of

00:07:18.449 --> 00:07:23.689
temperance realized that women would be a
more powerful ally against alcohol if they

00:07:23.689 --> 00:07:26.869
could vote.
Thanks Thought Bubble. So, in 1928, critic

00:07:26.869 --> 00:07:31.189
Gilbert Seldes wrote that if prohibition had
existed in 1800, “the suffragists might

00:07:31.189 --> 00:07:35.209
have remained for another century a scattered
group of intellectual cranks.”

00:07:35.209 --> 00:07:38.659
And to quote another historian, “the most
urgent reasons for women to want to vote in

00:07:38.659 --> 00:07:43.369
the mid-1800s were alcohol related: They wanted
the saloons closed down, or at least regulated.

00:07:43.369 --> 00:07:47.169
The wanted the right to own property, and
to shield their families’ financial security

00:07:47.169 --> 00:07:51.089
from the profligacy of drunken husbands. They
wanted the right to divorce those men, and

00:07:51.089 --> 00:07:55.169
to have them arrested for wife beating, and
to protect children from being terrorized

00:07:55.169 --> 00:07:59.919
by them. To do all these things they needed
to change the laws that consigned married

00:07:59.919 --> 00:08:04.419
women to the status of chattel. And to change
those laws, they needed the vote.”

00:08:04.419 --> 00:08:07.699
Many women were also important contributors
to the anti-slavery movement, although they

00:08:07.699 --> 00:08:11.909
tended to have more subordinate roles. Like,
abolitionist Maria Stewart was the first African

00:08:11.909 --> 00:08:16.539
American woman to lecture to mixed male and
female audiences. Harriet Beecher Stowe wrote

00:08:16.539 --> 00:08:21.089
the terrible but very import ant Uncle Tom’s
Cabin. Sarah and Angelina Grimke, daughters

00:08:21.089 --> 00:08:25.669
of a South Carolina slaveholder, converted
to Quakerism and became outspoken critics

00:08:25.669 --> 00:08:28.159
of slavery.
Sarah Grimke even published the Letters on

00:08:28.159 --> 00:08:32.060
the Equality of the Sexes in 1838, which is
pretty much what the title suggests.

00:08:32.060 --> 00:08:35.279
By the way, Stan, you could have made Sarah
Grimke’s letters the Mystery Document. I

00:08:35.279 --> 00:08:37.379
would have gotten that.
But I want to say one more thing about Harriet

00:08:37.379 --> 00:08:40.829
Beecher Stowe. There’s a reason we read
Uncle Tom’s Cabin in history classes and

00:08:40.829 --> 00:08:45.720
not in literature ones, but Uncle Tom’s
Cabin introduced millions of Americans to

00:08:45.720 --> 00:08:48.690
the idea that African American people were
people.

00:08:48.690 --> 00:08:53.050
At least in 19th century readers, Uncle Tom’s
Cabin humanized slaves to such a degree that

00:08:53.050 --> 00:08:57.120
it was banned throughout most of the south.
So many women involved in the abolitionist

00:08:57.120 --> 00:09:00.089
movement, when studying slavery, noticed that
there was something a little bit familiar.

00:09:00.089 --> 00:09:04.360
Now, some male abolitionists, notably Frederick
Douglass and William Lloyd Garrison became

00:09:04.360 --> 00:09:08.910
supporters of women’s rights, but ultimately
the male leaders of the anti-slavery movement

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:13.290
denied women’s demands for equality, believing
that any calls for women’s rights would

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:16.699
undermine the cause of abolition.
And they may have had a point because slavery

00:09:16.699 --> 00:09:21.110
only existed in parts of the country whereas
women existed in all of it.

00:09:21.110 --> 00:09:25.449
In fact, one of the arguments used by pro-slavery
forces was that equality under the law for

00:09:25.449 --> 00:09:30.420
male slaves might lead to a slippery slope
ending with, like, equality for WOMEN.

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:34.250
And out of this emerging consciousness of
their own subordinate position, the movement

00:09:34.250 --> 00:09:39.100
for women’s rights was born. The most visible
manifestation of it was the issue of woman’s

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:44.170
suffrage, raised most eloquently at the Seneca
Falls Convention of 1848 where Elizabeth Cady

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:48.139
Stanton, Lucretia Mott, Susan B. Anthony and
many others wrote and published the Declaration

00:09:48.139 --> 00:09:51.180
of Sentiments, modeled very closely on the
Declaration of Independence.

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:55.220
Except, in some ways this declaration was
much more radical than the Declaration of

00:09:55.220 --> 00:09:58.360
Independence because it took on the entire
patriarchal structure.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:01.519
Okay, so there are three things I want to
quickly point out about the 19th century movement

00:10:01.519 --> 00:10:06.000
for women’s rights. First, like abolitionism,
it was an international movement. Often American

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.420
feminists travelled abroad to find allies,
prefiguring the later transatlantic movement

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:14.639
of other advocates for social justice like
Florence Kelley and W.E.B DuBois.

00:10:14.639 --> 00:10:18.540
Secondly, for the most part, like other reform
movements, the women’s movement was primarily

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:22.769
a middle-class or even upper class effort.
Most of the delegates at Seneca Falls, for

00:10:22.769 --> 00:10:26.389
instance, were from the middle class. There
were no representatives of, like, cotton mills,

00:10:26.389 --> 00:10:30.730
but this didn’t mean that 19th century feminists
didn’t acknowledge the needs of working

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:32.889
women.
Like, Sojourner Truth, probably the most famous

00:10:32.889 --> 00:10:37.970
black woman abolitionist, spoke eloquently
of the plight of working class women, especially

00:10:37.970 --> 00:10:42.149
slaves, since she’d been one until 1827.
And other women recognized that women needed

00:10:42.149 --> 00:10:45.939
to be able to participate in the market economy
to gain some economic freedom.

00:10:45.939 --> 00:10:50.060
Now, of course all the women who wrote about
the moral evils of 19th century America or

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:55.089
spoke out or took hatchets to saloons were
doing what we would now recognize as work.

00:10:55.089 --> 00:10:58.410
But they were not being paid.
Amelia Bloomer got paid, though, because she

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:03.060
recognized that it was impossible for women
to easily participate in economic activities

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:06.430
because of their crazy clothes.
So she popularized a new kind of clothing

00:11:06.430 --> 00:11:09.680
featuring a loose fitting tunic, trousers,
and eponymous undergarments.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:13.579
But then Bloomer and her pants were ridiculed
in the press and in the streets, and this

00:11:13.579 --> 00:11:17.839
brings up the third important thing to remember
about the 19th century women’s movement.

00:11:17.839 --> 00:11:22.370
It faced strong resistance.
Patriarchy, like the force, is strong, which

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:28.199
is why Luke and Yoda and Darth Vader and Obi-Wan
and whoever Samuel Jackson played...all dudes.

00:11:28.199 --> 00:11:32.279
By the way, why did they train Luke up and
not Princess Leia who was cooler and had more

00:11:32.279 --> 00:11:36.310
to fight for and was less screwed up? Patriarchy.
Many women’s rights advocates were fighting

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:41.139
to overturn not just laws, but also attitudes.
Some of those goals, such as claiming greater

00:11:41.139 --> 00:11:44.959
control over the right to regulate their own
sexual activity and whether or not to have

00:11:44.959 --> 00:11:49.399
children were twisted by critics to claim
that women advocated “free love.”

00:11:49.399 --> 00:11:53.269
It’s interesting to note that the United
States ended slavery more than 50 years before

00:11:53.269 --> 00:11:57.149
it granted women the right to vote and that
although much of the march towards equality

00:11:57.149 --> 00:12:01.269
between the sexes has been slow and steady,
the Equal Rights Amendment, despite being

00:12:01.269 --> 00:12:05.379
passed by Congress, was never ratified.
But by taking leading roles in the reform

00:12:05.379 --> 00:12:08.779
movements in the 19th century, not just when
it came to temperance and slavery, but also

00:12:08.779 --> 00:12:13.370
prisons and asylums, women were able to enter
the public sphere for the first time.

00:12:13.370 --> 00:12:18.600
And these great women changed the world for
better and for worse, just as great men do.

00:12:18.600 --> 00:12:22.509
And along the way, they made “the woman
question” part of the movement for social

00:12:22.509 --> 00:12:27.889
reform in the United States. And in doing
so, American women chipped away at the idea

00:12:27.889 --> 00:12:31.980
that a woman’s place must be in the home.
That might not have been a presidential election

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:37.129
or a war, but it is still bringing real change
to our real lives on a daily basis. Thanks

00:12:37.129 --> 00:12:41.110
for watching. I’ll see you next week.
